{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c1ef0413-2c7b-43a9-9996-f0ab5fd86b76","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                        # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> \\\n  --profile cpu-sampling \\\n  --duration 00:00:30                  # 30s is usually enough\n```\n\n**3. Copy the trace out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** — open `trace.nettrace` in Visual Studio, VS Perfview, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (convert first with `dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the pod, use a **sidecar** or bake `dotnet-trace` into your image for production readiness.\n- For **off-CPU** analysis (thread pool starvation, lock contention), add `--providers Microsoft-DotNETCore-SampleProfiler` or consider `dotnet-counters` first to narrow down the issue.\n- `--duration` avoids runaway trace sizes — start short.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e8059533-27c2-4d84-989b-1c86aedc6116","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":423,"requestId":"D80A:19EA6:33C6ED4:38A0E08:69FBEB43"},"id":"ec193a50-40d4-43af-9997-1dbdaa382989","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:30:55.410Z","parentId":"8faf6ef1-ab04-4d0b-b5a9-508491bf4bb2"}
